------------------------------------------------------------------
1. IAM Policy (identity-based)
Attached to: User / Role / Lambda role
Controls: “What this role can do” ✅ (your issue)
2. Bucket Policy (resource-based)
Attached to: S3 bucket
Controls: “Who can access this bucket”

👉 Your error explicitly says:

no identity-based policy allows…

So fixing bucket policy alone won’t solve it.

✅ Fix (for your Lambda role)

Attach this policy to your role:

Role:

serverless-nodejs-project-prod-ap-south-1-lambdaRole
Minimal working policy:
{
  "Effect": "Allow",
  "Action": "s3:PutObject",
  "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::s3-image-lambda-demo/original/*"
}
🔥 Recommended (for your image service)

Since you're using image processing (sharp earlier), use this:

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "UploadImages",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:PutObject"
      ],
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::s3-image-lambda-demo/original/*"
    },
    {
      "Sid": "ReadImages",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:GetObject"
      ],
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::s3-image-lambda-demo/*"
    }
  ]
}
⚠️ When do you need Bucket Policy?

Only if:

Cross-account access
Public uploads
Restricting access at bucket level
Using signed URLs with strict conditions

👉 For your case (Lambda in same account): IAM is enough

🚀 Debug Checklist
 Policy attached to correct role?
 Role attached to Lambda?
 Correct bucket name (s3-image-lambda-demo)?
 Correct path (original/*)?
